Apparently there is a solution by way of a feature in [Preview.App in
MacOSX](http://twitter.com/wolframkriesing/status/222678037630693376) or one
could just [edit the PDF in GIMP and paste in one's signate
copy](http://twitter.com/edent/status/222678592092508160).

Of course a PNG of your signature sounds a bit dangerous. But in practice, this is what people do!

It gets even more WEIRD when one can sign using [Echo Sign](http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/EchoSign) by just typing your full name in a field. Er... this isn't secure now is it?

<a href="http://www.flickr.com/photos/hendry/7064697325/" title="Apparently this is legally binding by Kai Hendry, on Flickr"><img src="http://farm8.staticflickr.com/7105/7064697325_e78185c2d4.jpg" width="500" height="376" alt="Apparently this is legally binding"></a>

So we've gone from hand written signatures, where I guess a hand writing
specialist could detect a fraud. To 2012 when if you can type my full name you
could probably enter me in an agreement.

I can't help but think than legal hawks should think about developing better
technology for identifying parties in agreements. Then again when we have click
throughs on 100 page like T&Cs, one has to wonder... how the fuck did we get
here?
